{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:08:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"335"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/335"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.07,0.35,0.34,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"335"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/335"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"335"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89317"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 58-year-old man is admitted with an eight-hour history of colicky abdominal pain radiating down into his left groin. Over the last two hours, he has had uncontrollable shivers and shakes and worsening left loin pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 80/50 mmHg, pulse 100/min, and temperature 38\u00b0C. There is tenderness in his left flank. Urinalysis shows red cells and neutrophils. A CT scan shows a stone at the left pelvi-ureteric junction with mild hydronephrosis and perinephric stranding. He is given 2 L of isotonic saline and intravenous antibiotics are started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter three hours his blood pressure is 110/65 mmHg and his urine output has been 30 ml since admission. His serum creatinine is 230 umol/L (50 - 120) and potassium is 6.4 mmol/L (3.5 - 4.9). An ECG is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous calcium chloride","Intravenous normal saline","Ureteroscopy and stenting","Intravenous insulin and glucose","Rectal sodium polystyrene sulfonate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s underlying pathology is an infected, obstructed ureteric stone. The resulting acute kidney injury has resulted in hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESite-specific guidelines will vary on their categorisation of mild / moderate / severe hyperkalaemia, and these local guidelines should be consulted in practice. Nonetheless, with a potassium of 6.4mmol/L in this case the patient certainly has at least moderate hyperkalaemia and warrants potassium-lowering intervention. The most pressing concern in hyperkalaemia is cardiomyocyte irritability that can precipitate life-threatening arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous insulin and glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is the best answer. Insulin shifts potassium into cells in a dose-dependent manner by stimulating sodium/hydrogen antiporter channels on the cell membrane, causing sodium influx, which in turn stimulates the sodium/potassium ATPase, causing a potassium influx. 10 units of IV insulin reliably lowers serum potassium by 1mmol/L within 10-20 minutes and lasting for 4-6 hours. However, unsurprisingly, there is a risk of hypoglycaemia with exogenous insulin administration; therefore, most hospital guidelines recommend co-administration of a glucose solution. It is important to note that this method does not reduce whole-body potassium (merely temporarily shifting it from the extracellular compartment to the intracellular).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDefinitive treatment to promote potassium excretion should be instituted once the risk of cardiac instability is mitigated before putting the patient under general anaesthesia (in this case, proceeding to relieve the obstructive uropathy via a \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric stent\u003C/strong\u003E). Hyperkalaemia can interfere with many anaesthetic medications including paralysing agents, therefore pre-operative optomisation is critical. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the ECG demonstrated any of the features associated with hyperkalaemia (e.g. peaked T waves, P wave flattening, QRS widening, conduction blocks), then administration of a calcium salt (e.g.\u003Cstrong\u003E calcium chloride)\u003C/strong\u003E to stabilise the cardiac membranes would be indicated; importantly, \u003Cem\u003Ethis does not affect serum potassium concentration and further potassium-lowering treatment is required\u003C/em\u003E. An ECG is prudent in all cases to check for these features. In severe cases (typically with potassium over 7mmol/L), even in the absence of these changes it is reasonable to administer a calcium salt. However, in the case presented, there isn\u0027t yet a strong indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium polystyrine sulfonate (Resonium) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an ion-exchange resin and helps in decreasing serum potassium levels by exchanging its sodium ion with extracellular potassium in the gut. However, due to slow onset of action (\u0026gt;2 hours), uncertain efficacy, and the potential for adverse effects (it has been associated with colonic necrosis), it is not recommended for acute potassium lowering. It could be administered as an adjunct to the above, but is not the mainstay in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV saline\u003C/strong\u003E is not required since this patient is haemodynamically stable and has already received 2L of IV saline. Further infusion with saline raises the risk of volume overload.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serum potassium levels exceeding 6.0 mmol/L require some form of prompt intervention to either lower potassium levels or to facilitate membrane stabilisation.","Insulin with glucose is the most rapid and reliable method for temporarily lowering serum potassium by shifting it intracellularly.","Definitive management of obstructive uropathy with acute kidney injury requires relief of the obstruction after initial stabilisation."],"references":["Maxwell AP, Linden K, O\u0027Donnell S, Hamilton PK, McVeigh GE. Management of hyperkalaemia. J R Coll Physicians Edinb. 2013;43(3):246\u201351. Available from: https://europepmc.org/article/med/24087806","Li T, Vijayan A. Insulin for the treatment of hyperkalemia: a double-edged sword? Clin Kidney J. 2014 Jun;7(3):239\u201341. doi: 10.1093/ckj/sfu049. PMID: 25852882; PMCID: PMC4377764. Available from: https://europepmc.org/article/med/25852882"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89317"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"335"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89317"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T14:13:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T14:14:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"335"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"em